fields.description:
This fantastic, must see, Color Classic from 1935 offers a remarkable example of the Fleischers' vision, creativity and technical inventiveness. A prescursor to today's music videos, it includes 3-D effects.

The Cat's moon-walking dance moves, in which one appears to be pulled backwards while trying to walk forward, had actually been performed as early as 1932 by Cab Calloway (check him out in another Fleischer classic, “Minnie the Moocher”). At the time, this move was known at “The Buzz,” later it became one of Michael Jackson's signature moves known, interestingly, as "The Moonwalk." 

The enchanting 3-D effect used throughout this cartoon was achieved through the use of one of the Fleischer's numerous inventions; the Stereoptical Camera, or “set-back” in which actual miniature sets were built to serve as background for the animated characters. The Fleischers often used popular music of the day as the launching pad for their work; very much  like music videos are built around pop songs today.

fields.description:
Max held a number of positions after leaving Fleischer Studios, including serving as Head of Animation for long-time friend and colleague Jamison (Jam) Handy. 

It was around 1943, while working for the Jam Handy Organization, that Max produced News Sketches.

Located in Detroit, Handy’s Studio focused chiefly on industrial and commercial animation including military training films, educational shorts and films for the auto industry; but it is perhaps best known for the 1944 animated classic, “Rudolph, the Red-Nosed Reindeer." Directed by Max, “Rudolph” was one of the studio’s few theatrical releases and the first animated version of what was, at the time, a new Christmas story.

Max was given wide latitude to develop material he found interesting while at Handy. The News Sketches - a series of hand-drawn illustrations of amusing human-interest stories – were one of a number of projects Max created during this time. Although they appear to have been created for a theatrical audience, little specific information exists about where or when they were shown. This 6-minute clip seems to be one of the few films (if, in fact, there were more) from the series.

The Jam Handy Organization was a good match for Max, as he had long been interested in educational films (and having worked on military training films earlier in this career). Max continued to work with Jam Handy until he resigned in 1953.
